    "text": "It can work — but how you add it matters more than whether you do. With manual logging I have no heart-rate or recovery data to sanity-check your current load; the one number I can see is last night's 7.3 hours of sleep, which is a good base to build on. So borrow the structure that protects runners who can't monitor: swap an existing easy run for the new session rather than stacking extra volume on top, keep the two hard days separated by a couple of easy days, and start the new session noticeably shorter than your established one. Hold that layout for a few weeks before growing it. If your easy runs start feeling laboured, that is your data — drop back to one quality day.",
